Spanish Stocks: Gas Natural, NH Hoteles, Gamesa, Solaria Move

-- B y   M a n u e l   B a i g o r r i
-- 
2011-03-28T16:05:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-27/santander-sacyr-telefonica-bankinter-spanish-equity-preview.html
Spain ’s IBEX 35 index gained 40.6,
or 0.4 percent, to 10,751 at the 5:30 p.m. close in  Madrid . The
 Madrid Stock Exchange General Index (MADX)  also rose 0.4 percent today.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
Spanish market. Symbols are in parentheses after company names.  Gamesa Corporacion Tecnologica SA (GAM)   jumped 5.6
percent to 7.31 euros, the largest gain in a month. Renewable-
energy shares gained across  Europe  as the Greens defeated
Chancellor  Angela Merkel ’s coalition in German state elections.  Separately, Renewable energy mergers and acquisition
activity increased last year as confidence returned to the
market and sellers priced assets more realistically, the global
accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP said.  Abengoa SA (ABG)   climbed 5.8 percent to 23.80 euros and
 Acciona SA (ANA)   rose 1.7 percent to 78.95 euros.  Gas Natural SDG SA (GAS)   increased 1.7 percent to 12.93
euros, erasing March 25’s loss. Spain’s largest gas company was
raised to “buy” from “neutral” at BofA Merrill Lynch Global
Research.  NH Hoteles SA (NHH)   climbed for the first day in three,
jumping 2.6 percent to 4.88 euros. The Spanish hotelier replaced
 Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles SA  (CAF SM) on
Banesto Bolsa’s list of top picks for Spanish smallcaps,
according to a note sent to investors today.  Obrascon Huarte Lain SA (OHL)   advanced for a third day
in four, adding 1.8 percent to 25.76 euros. The Spanish
engineering and building company plans to compete for rail-
transportation contracts through its Guinovart Rail unit, El
Economista reported, citing comments from Chairman Juan-Miguel Villar Mir.  Solaria Energia & Medio Ambiente SA (SLR)   soared for a
fifth day, surging 10 percent to 2.44 euros. The Spanish solar-
panel maker sold 159,063 shares from March 16 to March 25 at
2.26 to 2.31 euros apiece, it said in a regulatory filing.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Manuel Baigorri in Madrid at 
 mbaigorri@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
